>

\pagebreakNum

### Felhound

The bloodhounds of the Legion, though their resemblance to canines is superficial. If their scaly bodies, eyeless faces, long and toothy maws, hoofed feet and strange, almost flower-like tentacular feelers extending from their shoulders can be ignored, then their behaviour can be called canine - their intense desire to chase and hunt down their targets, and an inbuilt obedience to domineering masters. Felhounds of all kinds are blind, and see through an innate ability to sense magic, for which they hunger constantly. When commanded, they will weaken their spellcasting prey by devouring the very magic used against them, and then will use their splayed tentacles to drain the mana and life of whatever creature is unfortunate enough to cross them.


> ##### Variant: Felstalker
> Less common than felhounds, but more dangerous, felstalkers lack the tentacle attacks of their demonic cousins. Instead, they gain the following stat changes.
> ___
> **Armor Class** 15 (natural armor)
> <br>**Hit Points** 65 (10d8 + 20)
> <br>**Challenge** 3 (700 XP)
> ___
> ***Pack Tactics.*** The felstalker has advantage on an attack roll against a creature if at least one of the felstalker's allies is within 5 feet of the creature and the ally isn't incapacitated.
> ___
> ***Bite.*** *Melee Weapon Attack:* +5 to hit, reach 5 ft., one target. *Hit:* 10 (2d4 + 5) piercing damage and the target must make a DC 12 Constitution saving throw or be afflicted by Fel Disease.
> <br>    A target afflicted by Fel Disease takes 1d8 necrotic damage at the start of each turn. The felstalker that inflicted this disease on the target regains hit points equal to half the necrotic damage. A target can only be inflicted with Fel Disease from one source. The target can repeat its saving throw at the end of each round to end the effect, or the affliction can be removed by any effect which cures diseases or dispels magic.

