### Felsteed

Even warlocks have the need for steeds, and no mere horse would be fitting for masters of such power. For this reason the felsteed was created from the native creatures of Azeroth, warped and corrupted into obedient minions like the others. No longer able to be called a horse, the felsteed is a warped demonic creature with flame in its blood, and hate and pain in its eyes. 

***Dreadsteeds of Xoroth.*** The felsteed is but a shallow copy of the true steed of demonic masters; the dreadsteed from the Legion world, Xoroth. Flaming hooves, curved horns and fiery breath crown the demon horse, not merely corrupted from nature but born purely of the Fel. A significantly more difficult and complicated ritual is required by warlocks to even see one of these horses.

\pagebreak

### Imp
*"Ohhh, sure! Send the little guy!"*

The fodder of the Legion, the lowest in the hierarchy. Weak, expendable, too numerous to count, and able to be spawned on an almost industrial scale, fiery imps make up an appreciable portion of the Legion's invasion tactics, often being deployed in swarms at areas and allowed to go hog wild. Imps have an innate, gleeful love for destruction, and when uncontrolled will happily use their fire magic to burn anything around them with zero hesitation. Their tiny, pathetic bodies contain an unbearable amount of pure energetic enthusiasm, and their love for burning is perhaps only matched for their love of talking, which makes them extremely unpopular among the other rank and file of the Legion. It is a favourite pastime of any demon commander to order a squad of imps to charge to their deaths, knowing that whether or not they destroy anything, the universe will benefit from fewer imps.

***Devilish Familiars.*** Imps are an extremely common sight among warlocks, even outside of the Legion's command, as they are easy to summon and control, are obedient, and easy to replace. As such they are often used as assistants or familiars by summoners with a need for an extra pair of hands, but little concern with what happens to them.

***Speculative Origins.*** Legend among imps is that they came from a world full of creatures like themselves who had a fondness for mischief and fun, but which spawned as spirits of nature. The truth of it is unknown, and demon lords will forbid any talk of such things, but it is nevertheless a comforting thought for imps everywhere, that they may have once come from somewhere.

***Fel Imps.*** Some imps are far larger than others, and burn with brighter flames of sickly green Fel. Whether this is a natural development or a mutation caused by experimentation by uncaring masters is unknown, but these rare Fel imps are seldom a welcome sight, as their fiery magic can be far more powerful.

___
> ## Imp
